Among these poets, those particularly skilled in waka were referred to as '''Kasei''' (歌聖).<ref>{{Cite Kotobank|word=歌聖|encyclopedia=精選版 日本国語大辞典、デジタル大辞泉|accessdate=2022-11-11}}</ref> This term not only expressed respect but also referred to poets worshiped as gods in the field of {{ill|kado|ja|歌道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kado|qq=}} (the way of waka). Specifically, based on descriptions in the preface to the {{ill|Kokin Wakashū|ja|古今和歌集|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokin Wakashū|qq=}}, it included Kakinomoto no Hitomaro and {{ill|Yamabe no Akahito|ja|山部赤人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamabe no Akahito|qq=}}. Other figures regarded as gods in kado included {{ill|Sumiyoshi Myōjin|ja|住吉明神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Myōjin|qq=}} and {{ill|Otō-no-Hime|ja|衣通姫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otō-no-Hime|qq=}}. From these, three were sometimes chosen as the '''Three Gods of Waka''' (和歌三神).<ref>{{Cite Kotobank|word=和歌三神|encyclopedia=精選版 日本国語大辞典、デジタル大辞泉、歌舞伎・浄瑠璃外題よみかた辞典、デジタル大辞泉プラス|accessdate=2022-11-11}}</ref> In modern tanka, {{ill|Saitō Mokichi|ja|斎藤茂吉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitō Mokichi|qq=}} is sometimes referred to as a Kasei.

However, interpretations of the preface to the Kokin Wakashū differ. One view holds that "Kasei" refers solely to Kakinomoto no Hitomaro, with Yamabe no Akahito considered a {{ill|Kasen|ja|歌仙|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kasen|qq=}} (poetic sage). This interpretation is based on differences in the text: Hitomaro is described as "正三位柿本人麿なむ歌の聖なりける" ("Kakinomoto no Hitomaro, Senior Third Rank, was a saint of poetry"), while Akahito is introduced with "また山の辺赤人といふ人ありけり" ("There was also a man named Yamabe no Akahito"). The phrases "なりける" ("was a saint") and "ありけり" ("was there") are interpreted as distinct. Nonetheless, later text states, "人麿は赤人が上に立たむことかたく　赤人は人麿が下に立たむことかたくなむありける" ("Hitomaro could not be placed above Akahito, nor could Akahito be placed below Hitomaro"), suggesting that they are of equal standing as poets.{{Citation needed|date=2015th year 9月}}

In modern times, many poets belong to {{ill|tanka societies|ja|結社#文学における結社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tanka societies|qq=}} and publish their works in magazines associated with these groups. When their tanka, poetic theories, or book reviews generate royalties, or when they receive payment for lectures, critiques, education, public awareness campaigns, or poetry selection activities, they are often called "specialist poets" (専門歌人). However, even many renowned "specialist poets" find it difficult to make a living solely from their poetry, so the term "professional poet" (プロ歌人) is not commonly used. Conversely, those who primarily submit works to newspaper columns are called "newspaper poets" (新聞歌人) or "contributing poets" (投稿歌人). Recently, "net poets" (ネット歌人) have also emerged, publishing their works on personal websites and blogs.

The community of poets is sometimes referred to as the '''Kadan''' (歌壇). In official institutions, there is a position called {{ill|Imperial Household Agency Goyōkake|ja|宮内庁御用掛|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Household Agency Goyōkake|qq=}}, which involves instructing the imperial family in tanka. Additionally, selectors exist to review submissions for the Imperial {{ill|Utakai Hajime|ja|歌会始|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utakai Hajime|qq=}}.

=== Supplementary Notes ===
Of the {{ill|Six Poetic Immortals|ja|六歌仙|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Six Poetic Immortals|qq=}}, five are included in the {{ill|Hyakunin Isshu|ja|百人一首|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hyakunin Isshu|qq=}}, and 15 are drawn from the {{ill|Thirty-Six Immortals of Poetry|ja|三十六歌仙|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Thirty-Six Immortals of Poetry|qq=}}.

